Introduction¶

In this report, you will find an analysis about "The movie database". To do this, I will start by taking a look at the dataset and brainstorming what questions could be answered. Then, I will use pandas and NumPy to answer the questions I'm most interested in, and share the answers.

The findings that you can find here are tentative, and this project is open-ended in that we are not looking for one right answer.

Chosen dataset¶

Since I'm a big fan of movies, I selected "TMDb database" dataset from a list included in the following document.

This dataset contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb),including user ratings and revenue.

  • Certain columns, like ‘cast’and ‘genres’, contain multiple values separated by pipe (|) characters.
  • There are some odd characters in the ‘cast’ column. These will be leaved as they are.
  • The final two columns ending with “_adj” show the budget and revenue of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time.

Getting Organized¶

I have selected to submit the project in this Jupyter notebook, so you will find in here:

  • The code I wrote, and
  • The report of my findings.

To analyze the data: brainstorming of questions¶

Question given with the data set:

  • Which genres are most popular from year to year?
  • What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?

My personal questions:

  • Is there any relationship between popularity and budget?
  • What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high vote?

Sharing findings¶

The report of my findings and the analysis is shown as a markdown cell after every code cell.

This report contains also a pdf version.

Analysis

  • The "id" column will not be analized since it does not add valuable information
  • "Popularity" column has a max of 32.98 and a min value of 0.000065 with a mean of 0.65. It seems that the max value is an outlier, so this column require further analysis
  • Over the 50% of the "budget" and "revenue" values are 0, but the 75% cut, mean and standard deviation are tremendously high so it seems that few movies have lots of budget and revenues whereas the mayority of movies have almost 0. It can be interesting to make two different analysis (one with movies from the first 3 quartiles, and other with movies in the last quartile) to answer every question.
  • "Runtime" seems to be every movie duration (in minutes), but the max and the min values should be inspected to verify if they are correct.
  • "vote_count" and "vote_average" may be biased by movie release year (since probably there can be more votes in movies from the 90's to 2015), but the values distribution do not seem to have any outlier.
  • "release_year" column seems to have a normal distribution from 1960 to 2015 years but there is no need in float datatype so it should be corrected.
  • A priori, budget_adj and revenue_adj will report the same information that budget and revenue since this columns are only a monetary correction aplying the dollar inflation of 2010. But the analysis that I will do over budget and revenue values should be contrasted with budget_adj and revenue_adj in case that dollar inflation have a high impact on the analysis.

Analysis

  • We can see that "release_dates" like 1/1/00, need the year digits to be converted from "00" to "2000" before converting this column to datetime type.

  • Since we do not have questions that need the complete date, only the year, this conversion will be left to the last part of this report (if needed).

  • To answer questions that need "year", I will use "release_year" column which is skewed left.

  • It seems a priori that there are more movies released now than in the early years!!

Data Cleaning¶

Structure and problems that need to be corrected discussion¶

  1. Removing columns: There are columns that do not add information for this analysis: "id", "imdb_id", "homepage","tagline", "overview", "budget_adj", "revenue_adj" and "release_date". These will be dropped
  2. Dropping duplicated values: There is to check if there are duplicated values. Those will be dropped.
  3. Dropping rows with NaN values: "cast", "director", "genres" and "production_companies" have null values that I will need to drop
  4. Converting to string: "original_title", "director", "cast", "genres" and "production_companies" have data type object, but this should be string

year_list = []
new_dict = {}
for index, row in df_q1_grouped.iterrows():
    year_list.append(index)
    genre_dict = {'Action':0, 'Adventure':0,'Science Fiction':0, 'Thriller':0,'Fantasy':0,'Crime':0,'Western':0,
                  'Drama':0,'Family':0, 'Animation':0,'Comedy':0, 'Mystery':0, 'Romance':0, 'War':0,'History':0,
                  'Music':0,'Horror':0,'Documentary':0,'TV Movie':0,'Foreign':0}
    for genre in genres_list:
        genre_dict[genre] = row["genres"].count(genre) #esta asignando el conteo con su genero por cada genero por cada año
        new_dict[index] = genre_dict

Lets create revenue categories

In [53]:
# Creating a function to separate new categories
def make_revenue_ordinal(row):
    if row == 0:
        return "No revenue"
    if 0 < row <= 10e+05:
        return "Low revenue"
    if 10e+05 < row <= 10e+07:
        return "Medium revenue"
    if 10e+07 < row <= 10e+08:
        return "High revenue"
    if 10e+08 < row <= 2.781506e+09:
        return "Very high  revenue"

Answering the second question¶

These are the properties associated to high revenues movies:

  • Except for the first quarter, all the movies with high revenues also have budget major than US$30 millions
  • Every high revenue movie last at least 1 hour with 12 minutes
  • Every high revenue movie have at least a vote average of 4.2 and the mean is 6,36
  • The mean release_year is 2003 and the 50% cut is 2005, so probably the majority of high revenue movies were released between these dates

# It still shows high variability, so lets recall the revenue categorization and lets apply the same for budget feature

def make_budget_ordinal(row):
    if row == 0:
        return "No budget"
    if 0 < row <= 10e+05:
        return "Low budget"
    if 10e+05 < row <= 10e+06:
        return "Medium budget"
    if 10e+06 < row <= 10e+07:
        return "High budget"
    if 10e+07 < row <= 4.250000e+08:
        return "Very high  budget"
    else:
        return "?"

df_ppal["budget_ordinal"] = df_ppal["budget"].apply(make_budget_ordinal)

Conclusions¶

Principal conclusions

  • There where few columns with NaN values, but "keywords" and "production_company" features had more than 1000 (nearly 10% of the data). Since this is an important percentage of the total data amount and considering that there are not question directly related to these features, I dropped them. So my analysis is limited to the rest of the features, but I could keep the most of the data

  • I had to drop only almost 100 registers which held NaN values for "cast", "director" and "genres" features which are like 1% of the data, so I can think that this did not affect or bias my analysis and conclusions.

  • Almost every numerical feature, by the exception of vote_average, were highly skewed right and even some cases, like budget and revenue had like the 50% of the data in 0. So, it seems that for this 50% of the movies the data was not present so we really can not know for sure the impact. Even though, the other 50% of the data do allowed me to see relationships when I categorize them, specially between high revenues, budget and popopularity.

  • Even when the results were obtained only per this sample, I think that it can be extrapolated to the rest of the world since the cinema business have a wide reach and Globalization, Internet and Social Networks really help know every new movie, tv series or documentary in the market and is easy to share people's opinion to the world. It was expectable, for instance, that highly budget movies are more popular than films with lower budget.

  • I only missed movie theater attendance to get a better look at popularity.

  • We can not tell for sure that if a certain movie get a high budget will be popular, or will have a tremendous revenue or a high vote, since we did not deploy any statistical tests.

From Data Wrangling section

  • Over the 50% of the "budget" and "revenue" values are 0 and there are values between 1 and 100 dollars. All of these insights seems like this data is wrongly placed. I just checked a couple of films budgets in wikipedia and the budget did not match with the "0" values in the TMDb.
  • I tried to categorize correctily movies between films, tv series, docummentary, mini series looking "runtime" feature ranges, but there were always a movie too long that could be considered a tv-serie and a documentary too short that could be considered a film.
  • "vote_count" effectively were biased by the movie release_year. This can be noted looking at the scatter plots in this section (the most recent release_year, the higher the vote_counts. This behaviour could not be observed in "vote_average" feature.

From the exploratory analysis section

  • Since budget, revenue, votes_average and popularity features are numerical, and the first two presented a histogram highly skewed right, I had to categorize them. Only votes_average presented almost a normal distribution so the quartiles limits were used to make the bins.
  • Surprisingly, the most popular movies genre almost every year is "Drama". I personally believed that "Science Fiction" could be a strong candidate.
  • High revenue movies have also high budget, and better vote average than movies with lower revenues.
  • High budget movies are more popular than lower budget movies
  • Higher votes movies are more likely to reach major revenues (there are mor movies that have higher revenues in "high vote" category)

Final thoughts

Categorization allowed me to bring more insightful conclusions to numerical data. Groupby allowed me to separate the analysis per efery categorization group and matplotlib helped me with the visualization of the behaviour of this categories and their relationships.

To improve the quality of the data, I would recommend to scrap other movie databases webpage (even Wikipedia has helpful) information, specially budget and revenue features.

To finish this report I would like to thank Udacity for making this awesome course and such a guided detail that was really helpful.
